nd place. Based on long-term collaborative and ethnographic work with Native American communities and schools, the book examines the imposition of colonial language policies against the fluorescence of contemporary community-driven efforts to revitalize threatened mother tongues. Here, readers will meet those who are on the frontlines of Native American language revitalization every day. As their efforts show, even languages whose last native speaker is gone can be reclaimed through family-, community-, and school-based language planning. Offering a critical-theory view of language policy, and emphasizing Indigenous sovereignties and the perspectives of revitalizers themselves, the book shows how language regenesis is undertaken in social practice, the role of youth in language reclamation, the challenges posed by dominant language policies, and the prospects for Indigenous language and culture continuance current revitalization efforts hold.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEducation, BilingualzUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducationxPlanning. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducation. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLanguagesxRevival. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLanguagesxSocial aspects. 0aIntercultural communication. 0aLanguage planningxUnited States. 0aLanguage planningzUnited States. 0aLanguage policyxUnited States. 0aLanguage policyzUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh  aIndigenous language.  aNative America.  alanguage education.  alanguage planning.  alanguage policy.1 aGamble, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlebear, Richard E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarty, Teresa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato